#+title: ift6755-bounded-model-checking
#+STARTUP: latexpreview inlineimages
#+date: [2022-03-30 Wed 09:15]

* Bounded Model Checking

An approach to symbolic model-checking that uses SAT solvers - *Bounded Model Checking*

- Applications
  - A.I. Planning problems - Can we reach a desired state in $k$ steps?
  - Verification of safety properties - Can we find a bad state in $k$ steps?
  - Verification - Can we find a counterexample in $k$ steps?

Given - Transition system $M$, temporal logic formula $f$, user-supplied time bound $k$
Construct - Propositional formula $\Omega(k)$ that is *satisfiable* iff $f$ is valid along a path of length $k$

- Path of length $k$ - $I(s_0) \land \Big (\land^{k - 1}_{i = 0} R(s_i, s_{i + 1})\Big)$
  - Starting form the iniitial state, go $k$ steps forward

Say $f = \mathrm{EF} \ p$ ($p$ is reachable) and $k = 2$, then:
$\Omega(2) = I(s_0) \land R(s_0 \cdot s_1) \land R(s_1 \cdot s_2) \land (p_0 \lor p_1 \lor p_2)$

** Idea - Checking invariants

$\mathrm{AG} \ p$ means $p$ must hold in every state along any path of length $k$

We take $\lnot \Omega(k) = \Bigg (I(s_0) \land \Big (\land^{k - 1}_{i = 0} R(s_i, s_{i + 1})\Big) \Bigg) \to \land_{i = 0}^k p_i$
So $\Omega(k) = \Bigg (I(s_0) \land \Big (\land^{k - 1}_{i = 0} R(s_i, s_{i + 1})\Big) \Bigg) \land \Big(\lor_{i = 0}^k p_i\Big)$

** Example - Two-bit counter

Initial state - $I : \lnot l \land \lnot r$
Transition - $R: \begin{pmatrix} l' = (l \neq r) \land \\ r' = \lnot r \end{pmatrix}$
Safety propertiy - $\mathrm {AG} (\lnot l \lor \lnot r)$ (one of the digits must be 0)

$\Omega(2) : (\lnot l_0 \land \lnot r_0) \land \begin{pmatrix} l_1 = (l_0 \neq r_0) \land r_1 = \lnot r_0 \land \\ l_2 = (l_1 \neq r_1) \land r_2 = \lnot r_1 \end{pmatrix} \land \begin{pmatrix} (l_0 \land r_0) \lor \\ (l_1 \land r_1) \lor \\ (l_2 \land r_2) \end{pmatrix}$
- $\Omega(2)$ is unsatisfiable
- $\Omega(3)$ is satisfiable

